'''Courtney Paris''' (born September 21, 1987 in [[San Jose, California]]) was the senior starting center for the [[University of Oklahoma]] women's basketball team.  She is now a member of the WNBA's [[Chicago Sky]] basketball team. Her twin sister, current [[Los Angeles Sparks]] player [[Ashley Paris]], was also a [[Oklahoma Sooners|Sooner]].  

==Early life==
In addition to being [[Paris twins|a twin]], Paris has four brothers: Wayne, David, Austin and Brandon.  She has two stepbrothers (Bubba's sons) William III and Christian.  Her parents are Lynne Gray and former [[National Football League|NFL]] player [[Bubba Paris|William "Bubba" Paris]].

Paris transferred from Modesto Christian High School to [[Piedmont High School (Piedmont, California) and then|Millennium High School]] in [[Piedmont, California]], at the start of the 2002-2003 year. Paris was named a [[Women's Basketball Coaches Association|WBCA]] All-American.<ref name="HS All-Americans"/> She participated in the 2005 [[Women's_Basketball_Coaches_Association#WBCA_High_School_All-America_Game|WBCA High School All-America Game]], where she scored three points.<ref name="box score"/> Paris chose Oklahoma over UConn, California, Texas, UCLA, and Syracuse.

==College career==
Paris is the only player in [[NCAA]] history, male or female, to have 700 points, 500 rebounds, and 100 blocks in a season.  In 2005-06, Paris set the women's NCAA record for [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] in a single season, with 539.  She holds the NCAA record for most consecutive [[double-double]]s at 112 games, a streak which ended on February 2, 2009 against Pat Summitt and the Tennessee Lady Volunteers; however, Oklahoma won the game, denying Summitt her 1000th career victory.<ref name="soonersports">{{cite web | url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/w-baskbl/recaps/010409aaa.html | title=Oklahoma Sooners Official Athletic Site - Women's Basketball| publisher= CBS Interactive| date=2009-01-04|accessdate=2009-01-06}}</ref> On February 8, 2009, Paris broke the record for most career NCAA Division I rebounds, formerly held by Wanda Ford of [[Drake Bulldogs|Drake]].<ref name="Paris breaks Division 1 rebounding record">{{cite web | url=http://www.cbssports.com/ncaawbasketball/gamecenter/recap/NCAAW_20090208_OK@OKST | title=CBS Sports| publisher= CBS Interactive| date=2009-02-08|accessdate=2009-02-08}}</ref> In the Sooners' victory in the semifinals of the Oklahoma City Regional in the [[2009 NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Tournament|2009 NCAA Tournament]] against [[Pittsburgh Panthers women's basketball|Pitt]] on March 29, she became the first player in U.S. college basketball history<U+2014>regardless of sex, governing body, or division<U+2014>with 2,500 points and 2,000 rebounds in her career.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncw/recap?gameId=294000038 |title=Hand, Sooners overcome Paris' foul trouble to reach Elite Eight |author=Associated Press |publisher=''ESPN.com'' |date=2009-03-29 |accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref>

Paris also became the first freshman named to the [[Associated Press]] All-American team in 2006, and again made the team in 2007.<ref name="Oklahoma's Courtney Paris Is An All-American Again">{{cite web | url=http://www.kotv.com/sports/local/story/?id=123735 | title=Oklahoma's Courtney Paris Is An All-American Again|work=kotv.com| publisher= [[KOTV]]| date= 2007-03-29|accessdate=2007-08-22}}</ref> In April 2007, Paris was named the 2007 Associated Press Women's basketball player of the year. She is the first sophomore ever to win the AP Player of the year award.<ref name="Paris named Player of Year ">{{cite web | last=Jacobsen| first=Lynn| url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/article.aspx?articleID=070401_238_B1_hShei00833| title=
Paris named Player of Year | work= [[Tulsa World]] |date=2007-04-01| accessdate=2007-08-22}}</ref> She won [[All-American]] honors again her junior year, and as a senior she became the only four-time first-team [[All-American]] in women's basketball history.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncw/news/story?id=4030503 Courtney Paris Becomes Only 4-Time All-American] ESPN, March 31, 2009</ref> She also won the [[Lowe's Senior CLASS Award]], recognizing her as the nation's top senior women's basketball player.

At Oklahoma, Paris majored in [[journalism]].

Paris had announced that if Oklahoma did not win the NCAA championship in 2009, her final year, she would repay her scholarship<U+2014>worth about $64,000 in out-of-state tuition<U+2014>to the university. She said that without a championship, "I don<U+2019>t feel like I<U+2019>ve earned it.<U+201D><ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/24/sports/ncaabasketball/24win.html?_r=1&ref=sports Star's Vow to Win or Pay Stirs Women's Basketball] NY Times, March 23, 2009</ref>

On Sunday April 5, 2009, Oklahoma lost to the Louisville Cardinals 61-59. In a post-game interview with ESPN, Paris was asked if she would make do on her promise to repay her $64,000 basketball scholarship. She replied that she would but that it would take her some time. A week later, the university said that she did not have to repay her scholarship.

==Pro career==
Paris was selected by the [[Sacramento Monarchs]] at #7 in the [[2009 WNBA Draft]] and her sister was drafted to the [[Los Angeles Sparks]].

On December 14, 2009 the WNBA held a dispersal draft for the Monarchs' players. Courtney was taken with the fourth pick by the [[Chicago Sky]]. On May 12, 2010, Paris was waved by the Sky.<ref>[http://www.wnba.com/transactions/WNBA_2010.html WNBA Transactions] WNBA Transaction Page</ref>

